{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/sarif-2.1.0.json",
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "CodeGuard",
          "version": "1.0.0",
          "informationUri": "https://github.com/your-org/codeguard",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "javascript.lang.security.audit.sqli.node-mysql-sqli.node-mysql-sqli",
              "name": "node-mysql-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs an SQL query by directly concatenating a user-controlled `input` variable (which originates from `req.query.id`) into the SQL string. This direct string concatenation is highly vulnerable to SQL injection, as an attacker can embed malicious SQL syntax within the `input` to alter the query's logic, bypass authentication, or exfiltrate/manipulate data."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs an SQL query by directly concatenating a user-controlled `input` variable (which originates from `req.query.id`) into the SQL string. This direct string concatenation is highly vulnerable to SQL injection, as an attacker can embed malicious SQL syntax within the `input` to alter the query's logic, bypass authentication, or exfiltrate/manipulate data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.security.audit.express-check-csurf-middleware-usage.express-check-csurf-middleware-usage",
              "name": "express-check-csurf-middleware-usage",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application does not appear to have a Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection middleware (such as `csurf`) or explicit CSRF token validation implemented. This lack of protection makes the application vulnerable to CSRF attacks, where an attacker can trick an authenticated user into performing unintended actions on the application by sending forged requests from a different site."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application does not appear to have a Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection middleware (such as `csurf`) or explicit CSRF token validation implemented. This lack of protection makes the application vulnerable to CSRF attacks, where an attacker can trick an authenticated user into performing unintended actions on the application by sending forged requests from a different site."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "INFO",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.mysql.node-mysql-hardcoded-secret.node-mysql-hardcoded-secret",
              "name": "node-mysql-hardcoded-secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The database password, represented by `DB_PASSWORD`, is identified as being hardcoded directly within the application's source code. Hardcoding sensitive credentials makes them highly vulnerable to exposure if the codebase is accessed by unauthorized individuals (e.g., via a public repository, compromised build system, or internal leak), potentially leading to unauthorized database access."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The database password, represented by `DB_PASSWORD`, is identified as being hardcoded directly within the application's source code. Hardcoding sensitive credentials makes them highly vulnerable to exposure if the codebase is accessed by unauthorized individuals (e.g., via a public repository, compromised build system, or internal leak), potentially leading to unauthorized database access."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.mysql.express-mysql-sqli.express-mysql-sqli",
              "name": "express-mysql-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs an SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`req.query.id`) into the `query` string at line 44 (`const query = 'SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ' + id`). This `query` variable is then executed by `db.query` at line 53. This direct string concatenation of user input makes the application highly vulnerable to SQL injection, enabling attackers to inject malicious SQL code."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs an SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`req.query.id`) into the `query` string at line 44 (`const query = 'SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ' + id`). This `query` variable is then executed by `db.query` at line 53. This direct string concatenation of user input makes the application highly vulnerable to SQL injection, enabling attackers to inject malicious SQL code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep",
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.express-child-process.express-child-process",
              "name": "express-child-process",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application uses `child_process.exec` to execute a `command` string that is directly taken from user input (`req.query.cmd`). The `exec` function spawns a shell and executes the command string, making it susceptible to shell metacharacter injection. This direct execution without proper sanitization or validation makes the application highly vulnerable to command injection, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application uses `child_process.exec` to execute a `command` string that is directly taken from user input (`req.query.cmd`). The `exec` function spawns a shell and executes the command string, making it susceptible to shell metacharacter injection. This direct execution without proper sanitization or validation makes the application highly vulnerable to command injection, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.lang.security.detect-child-process.detect-child-process",
              "name": "detect-child-process",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly executes a command string (`req.query.cmd`) received from user input without any sanitization or validation. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary shell commands, leading to a Remote Command Execution (RCE) vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly executes a command string (`req.query.cmd`) received from user input without any sanitization or validation. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary shell commands, leading to a Remote Command Execution (RCE) vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "ERROR",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.security.injection.raw-html-format.raw-html-format",
              "name": "raw-html-format",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "User-supplied input (`req.query.q`) is directly embedded into the HTML response without proper sanitization or encoding. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "User-supplied input (`req.query.q`) is directly embedded into the HTML response without proper sanitization or encoding. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_cross_site_scripting",
              "name": "javascript_express_cross_site_scripting",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "User-supplied input (`req.query.q`) is directly embedded into the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "User-supplied input (`req.query.q`) is directly embedded into the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep",
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.express-fs-filename.express-fs-filename",
              "name": "express-fs-filename",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly constructs a file path (`fs.readFile(file, ...)`) using unsanitized user input (`req.query.file`). This allows an attacker to manipulate the file path using sequences like `../` to access or read files outside the intended directory, leading to a Path Traversal vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly constructs a file path (`fs.readFile(file, ...)`) using unsanitized user input (`req.query.file`). This allows an attacker to manipulate the file path using sequences like `../` to access or read files outside the intended directory, leading to a Path Traversal vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.jsonwebtoken.security.jwt-hardcode.hardcoded-jwt-secret",
              "name": "hardcoded-jwt-secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The JWT signing secret (`'secret'`) is hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability because if the secret is discovered (e.g., through code leaks, reverse engineering), an attacker can forge valid JWTs, impersonate users, and bypass authentication."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The JWT signing secret (`'secret'`) is hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability because if the secret is discovered (e.g., through code leaks, reverse engineering), an attacker can forge valid JWTs, impersonate users, and bypass authentication."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.jsonwebtoken.security.jwt-none-alg.jwt-none-alg",
              "name": "jwt-none-alg",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code explicitly allows the 'none' algorithm for JWT verification. This algorithm means no signature is expected or checked. An attacker can craft any token payload, set the 'alg' header to 'none', and the application will accept it as valid, effectively bypassing authentication or authorization checks. This is a severe integrity bypass vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The code explicitly allows the 'none' algorithm for JWT verification. This algorithm means no signature is expected or checked. An attacker can craft any token payload, set the 'alg' header to 'none', and the application will accept it as valid, effectively bypassing authentication or authorization checks. This is a severe integrity bypass vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "ERROR",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.mongodb.express-mongo-nosqli.express-mongo-nosqli",
              "name": "express-mongo-nosqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a Mongoose `findOne` query directly using user-supplied `username` and `password` from `req.body` without any sanitization or validation. An attacker can inject NoSQL query operators (e.g., `$ne`, `$gt`, `$or`) into these fields, manipulating the query logic to bypass authentication or gain unauthorized access to data."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a Mongoose `findOne` query directly using user-supplied `username` and `password` from `req.body` without any sanitization or validation. An attacker can inject NoSQL query operators (e.g., `$ne`, `$gt`, `$or`) into these fields, manipulating the query logic to bypass authentication or gain unauthorized access to data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep",
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "javascript_express_hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The JWT signing secret `'secret'` (line 120) is hardcoded directly into the application's source code. A hardcoded secret is easily discoverable if the source code is compromised or reverse-engineered. If an attacker knows the JWT signing secret, they can forge valid JWTs, impersonate users, and gain unauthorized access to protected resources without needing to authenticate."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The JWT signing secret `'secret'` (line 120) is hardcoded directly into the application's source code. A hardcoded secret is easily discoverable if the source code is compromised or reverse-engineered. If an attacker knows the JWT signing secret, they can forge valid JWTs, impersonate users, and gain unauthorized access to protected resources without needing to authenticate."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_nosql_injection",
              "name": "javascript_express_nosql_injection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly takes the `filter` parameter from the request query string (line 166), parses it as JSON, and uses the resulting object as a query for `mongoose.model('User').find()`. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary query operators (e.g., `$where`, `$gt`, `$ne`) or modify the query logic, leading to unauthorized data access, modification, or even authentication bypass depending on the context. This is a classic NoSQL Injection vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly takes the `filter` parameter from the request query string (line 166), parses it as JSON, and uses the resulting object as a query for `mongoose.model('User').find()`. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary query operators (e.g., `$where`, `$gt`, `$ne`) or modify the query logic, leading to unauthorized data access, modification, or even authentication bypass depending on the context. This is a classic NoSQL Injection vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_dynamic_os_command",
              "name": "javascript_lang_dynamic_os_command",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly takes the `cmd` parameter from the request query string (line 65) and executes it using `child_process.exec()`. There is no sanitization or validation of the user-provided input. This creates a critical Command Injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to inject arbitrary shell commands, which will be executed on the server with the privileges of the Node.js process."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly takes the `cmd` parameter from the request query string (line 65) and executes it using `child_process.exec()`. There is no sanitization or validation of the user-provided input. This creates a critical Command Injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to inject arbitrary shell commands, which will be executed on the server with the privileges of the Node.js process."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A Stripe test API key (`sk_test_...`) is hardcoded directly into the source code. Hardcoding any secret, even a test key, is a critical security vulnerability as it makes the credential accessible to anyone with access to the codebase. This can lead to unauthorized use or, if a similar pattern is used for live keys, a path to production compromise."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A Stripe test API key (`sk_test_...`) is hardcoded directly into the source code. Hardcoding any secret, even a test key, is a critical security vulnerability as it makes the credential accessible to anyone with access to the codebase. This can lead to unauthorized use or, if a similar pattern is used for live keys, a path to production compromise."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer",
                  "Gitleaks"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "javascript_lang_hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A database password (`DB_PASSWORD`) is hardcoded directly into the source code. Hardcoding sensitive credentials like database passwords is a severe security flaw because it exposes the password to anyone who can view the code, including developers, CI/CD systems, and potential attackers."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A database password (`DB_PASSWORD`) is hardcoded directly into the source code. Hardcoding sensitive credentials like database passwords is a severe security flaw because it exposes the password to anyone who can view the code, including developers, CI/CD systems, and potential attackers."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_jwt_hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "javascript_lang_jwt_hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application uses a hard-coded, weak secret (`'secret'`) to sign JSON Web Tokens (JWTs). This makes the tokens highly vulnerable to brute-force attacks or dictionary attacks, allowing an attacker to discover the secret. Once the secret is known, an attacker can forge arbitrary valid JWTs for any user, thereby bypassing authentication and impersonating users. The absence of an `expiresIn` option further means tokens, once compromised, remain valid indefinitely."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application uses a hard-coded, weak secret (`'secret'`) to sign JSON Web Tokens (JWTs). This makes the tokens highly vulnerable to brute-force attacks or dictionary attacks, allowing an attacker to discover the secret. Once the secret is known, an attacker can forge arbitrary valid JWTs for any user, thereby bypassing authentication and impersonating users. The absence of an `expiresIn` option further means tokens, once compromised, remain valid indefinitely."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_sql_injection",
              "name": "javascript_lang_sql_injection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`input`) into the query string without any form of sanitization, validation, or parameterization. This makes the application vulnerable to SQL injection, allowing an attacker to manipulate the query to gain unauthorized access to data, modify database records, or even execute arbitrary commands on the underlying database system."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`input`) into the query string without any form of sanitization, validation, or parameterization. This makes the application vulnerable to SQL injection, allowing an attacker to manipulate the query to gain unauthorized access to data, modify database records, or even execute arbitrary commands on the underlying database system."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_server_side_request_forgery",
              "name": "javascript_express_server_side_request_forgery",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application accepts a URL directly from user input (`req.query.url`) and then makes an HTTP request to that URL using `axios.get()`. This is a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability. An attacker can supply internal or local network URLs (e.g., `http://localhost`, `http://169.254.169.254` for AWS metadata, or internal IP addresses) to force the server to make requests to those locations. This can be used to scan internal networks, access sensitive internal services, bypass firewalls, or exploit trust relationships between the server and other internal systems."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application accepts a URL directly from user input (`req.query.url`) and then makes an HTTP request to that URL using `axios.get()`. This is a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability. An attacker can supply internal or local network URLs (e.g., `http://localhost`, `http://169.254.169.254` for AWS metadata, or internal IP addresses) to force the server to make requests to those locations. This can be used to scan internal networks, access sensitive internal services, bypass firewalls, or exploit trust relationships between the server and other internal systems."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_http_url_using_user_input",
              "name": "javascript_lang_http_url_using_user_input",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application uses user-controlled input (`req.body.url`) directly as the target URL for an `axios.post` request. An attacker can provide an arbitrary URL, forcing the server to make requests to internal network resources, cloud metadata APIs (e.g., AWS EC2 metadata service), or other external services, potentially leading to information disclosure, port scanning, or further attacks."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application uses user-controlled input (`req.body.url`) directly as the target URL for an `axios.post` request. An attacker can provide an arbitrary URL, forcing the server to make requests to internal network resources, cloud metadata APIs (e.g., AWS EC2 metadata service), or other external services, potentially leading to information disclosure, port scanning, or further attacks."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_non_literal_fs_filename",
              "name": "javascript_lang_non_literal_fs_filename",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a file path using unsanitized user input (`req.query.file`) and passes it directly to `fs.readFile`. An attacker can inject path traversal sequences (e.g., `../`) to read arbitrary files outside the intended directory, potentially accessing sensitive configuration files, source code, or credential files."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a file path using unsanitized user input (`req.query.file`) and passes it directly to `fs.readFile`. An attacker can inject path traversal sequences (e.g., `../`) to read arbitrary files outside the intended directory, potentially accessing sensitive configuration files, source code, or credential files."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_raw_html_using_user_input",
              "name": "javascript_lang_raw_html_using_user_input",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application embeds unsanitized user input (`req.query.q`) directly into the HTML response without any encoding. This creates a reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability, allowing an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code into the victim's browser, which will then be executed in the context of the application's domain."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application embeds unsanitized user input (`req.query.q`) directly into the HTML response without any encoding. This creates a reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability, allowing an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code into the victim's browser, which will then be executed in the context of the application's domain."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_helmet_missing",
              "name": "javascript_express_helmet_missing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application does not use Helmet.js middleware, which is an essential package for Express applications that sets various security-enhancing HTTP headers. Without Helmet, the application lacks protections against common client-side attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) via missing Content Security Policy, clickjacking via missing X-Frame-Options, MIME-type sniffing via missing X-Content-Type-Options, and more."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application does not use Helmet.js middleware, which is an essential package for Express applications that sets various security-enhancing HTTP headers. Without Helmet, the application lacks protections against common client-side attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) via missing Content Security Policy, clickjacking via missing X-Frame-Options, MIME-type sniffing via missing X-Content-Type-Options, and more."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_reduce_fingerprint",
              "name": "javascript_express_reduce_fingerprint",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application, by default, sends the `X-Powered-By: Express` header in its HTTP responses. This header reveals information about the server's technology stack, which can assist attackers in fingerprinting the application and targeting known vulnerabilities specific to Express or Node.js versions. While not a direct vulnerability, it provides useful reconnaissance information to potential attackers."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application, by default, sends the `X-Powered-By: Express` header in its HTTP responses. This header reveals information about the server's technology stack, which can assist attackers in fingerprinting the application and targeting known vulnerabilities specific to Express or Node.js versions. While not a direct vulnerability, it provides useful reconnaissance information to potential attackers."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_observable_timing",
              "name": "javascript_lang_observable_timing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application compares a user-supplied token (`req.body.token`) with a sensitive API token (`process.env.API_TOKEN`) using the standard JavaScript strict equality operator (`===`). This operator is not guaranteed to perform comparisons in constant time across all JavaScript engines and environments. An attacker could potentially perform a timing attack by sending various token prefixes and observing slight differences in response times. These timing discrepancies can reveal how many characters of the provided token match the sensitive stored token, allowing the attacker to progressively guess the full API token character by character."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application compares a user-supplied token (`req.body.token`) with a sensitive API token (`process.env.API_TOKEN`) using the standard JavaScript strict equality operator (`===`). This operator is not guaranteed to perform comparisons in constant time across all JavaScript engines and environments. An attacker could potentially perform a timing attack by sending various token prefixes and observing slight differences in response times. These timing discrepancies can reveal how many characters of the provided token match the sensitive stored token, allowing the attacker to progressively guess the full API token character by character."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "results": [
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.lang.security.audit.sqli.node-mysql-sqli.node-mysql-sqli",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application constructs an SQL query by directly concatenating a user-controlled `input` variable (which originates from `req.query.id`) into the SQL string. This direct string concatenation is highly vulnerable to SQL injection, as an attacker can embed malicious SQL syntax within the `input` to alter the query's logic, bypass authentication, or exfiltrate/manipulate data.\n\nExploit: An attacker could send a request that sets `input` to `1 OR 1=1 --`. The resulting query would be `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 1 OR 1=1 --`, which would return all records from the `users` table instead of just the user with ID 1, effectively bypassing access controls. More severe attacks like `1; DROP TABLE users; --` could also be attempted.\n\nFix: This fix uses a parameterized query. Instead of directly concatenating the user input, a placeholder `?` is used in the SQL string, and the `input` variable is passed as a separate argument to the `db.query` method. The database driver then properly escapes the input, preventing it from being interpreted as executable SQL code."
          },
