        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.express.security.audit.express-check-csurf-middleware-usage.express-check-csurf-middleware-usage",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[HIGH] The Express application does not appear to have a Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection middleware (such as `csurf`) or explicit CSRF token validation implemented. This lack of protection makes the application vulnerable to CSRF attacks, where an attacker can trick an authenticated user into performing unintended actions on the application by sending forged requests from a different site.\n\nExploit: If an authenticated user is tricked into visiting a malicious website, that website could craft and automatically submit a hidden form or an AJAX request to the vulnerable application's endpoint (e.g., a money transfer or password change endpoint). Since the user is authenticated, their browser would automatically include session cookies, making the forged request appear legitimate to the server, leading to an unauthorized action.\n\nFix: This fix involves integrating the `csurf` middleware along with `cookie-parser` into the Express application. The `csurf` middleware generates a unique CSRF token for each user, which must be included in all state-changing (POST, PUT, DELETE) requests. The server then verifies this token against the one stored in the session/cookie, preventing requests that originate from external, malicious sites."
          },
