        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.express.express-child-process.express-child-process",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application uses `child_process.exec` to execute a `command` string that is directly taken from user input (`req.query.cmd`). The `exec` function spawns a shell and executes the command string, making it susceptible to shell metacharacter injection. This direct execution without proper sanitization or validation makes the application highly vulnerable to command injection, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server.\n\nExploit: An attacker could send a request like `/run?cmd=ls -la` to list directory contents, or more maliciously, `/run?cmd=rm -rf /` (if permissions allow), or `/run?cmd=cat /etc/passwd` to read system files. They could also chain commands using `&&` or `;`, e.g., `/run?cmd=echo hello && id`, to execute multiple commands.\n\nFix: This fix implements several layers of defense. First, it introduces a strict whitelist for `allowedCommands`, ensuring that only explicitly permitted commands can be executed. Second, it switches from `child_process.exec` to `child_process.execFile`. `execFile` is safer because it directly executes the specified command without spawning a shell, preventing shell metacharacter injection. User-supplied input is passed as separate arguments, ensuring it is treated as data rather than executable code."
          },
          "locations": [
