        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.express.mongodb.express-mongo-nosqli.express-mongo-nosqli",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application constructs a Mongoose `findOne` query directly using user-supplied `username` and `password` from `req.body` without any sanitization or validation. An attacker can inject NoSQL query operators (e.g., `$ne`, `$gt`, `$or`) into these fields, manipulating the query logic to bypass authentication or gain unauthorized access to data.\n\nExploit: To bypass authentication, an attacker could send a request body like `{\"username\": {\"$ne\": null}, \"password\": {\"$ne\": null}}`. This query would find any user where both username and password are not null, effectively logging in as the first matching user. Another example for admin bypass could be `{\"username\": \"admin\", \"password\": {\"$gt\": \"\"}}` which might log in as admin without knowing the password.\n\nFix: Input values (username, password) should be explicitly validated and sanitized to ensure they are simple string literals and do not contain NoSQL operators or objects. For login scenarios, the best practice is to first query the user by a unique identifier (like username), then retrieve the stored hashed password and compare it with the provided plaintext password using a secure hashing algorithm (e.g., bcrypt). This prevents malicious NoSQL operators from being interpreted as part of the query structure and never queries with plaintext passwords directly."
          },
