            "text": "[CRITICAL] A JWT (JSON Web Token) secret (`JWT_SECRET`) is hardcoded into the source code. The JWT secret is crucial for signing and verifying the integrity of JWTs, which are commonly used for authentication and authorization. Hardcoding it makes it vulnerable to disclosure, compromising the security of tokens.\n\nExploit: If an attacker gains access to the source code and extracts `mysecretkey123`, they can then forge valid JWTs. This could allow them to create tokens for any user, including administrators, effectively bypassing authentication and authorization controls to gain unauthorized access to protected resources or elevate their privileges within the application.\n\nFix: Replace the hardcoded JWT secret with an environment variable. For production, the JWT secret should be a strong, cryptographically secure random string, and it must be managed through a secure secrets management system (e.g., AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault) to ensure it is never committed to source control and is securely loaded at runtime."
