          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_lang_raw_html_using_user_input",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[HIGH] The application embeds unsanitized user input (`req.query.q`) directly into the HTML response without any encoding. This creates a reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability, allowing an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code into the victim's browser, which will then be executed in the context of the application's domain.\n\nExploit: An attacker sends a crafted URL like `/search?q=<script>alert(document.cookie)</script>` to a victim. When the victim opens the URL, the injected script executes, displaying an alert box with their cookies (or performing more malicious actions like session hijacking, defacement, or redirecting to phishing sites).\n\nFix: Escape all HTML special characters in user-controlled input (`req.query.q`) before embedding it into the HTML response. This prevents the browser from interpreting the input as active content (like `<script>` tags, event handlers, etc.) and mitigates Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. Using an existing, well-vetted HTML escaping library is recommended for comprehensive protection."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 81
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "Escape all HTML special characters in user-controlled input (`req.query.q`) before embedding it into the HTML response. This prevents the browser from interpreting the input as active content (like `<script>` tags, event handlers, etc.) and mitigates Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. Using an existing, well-vetted HTML escaping library is recommended for comprehensive protection."
              },
              "artifactChanges": [
                {
                  "artifactLocation": {
                    "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                    "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                  },
                  "replacements": [
                    {
                      "deletedRegion": {
                        "startLine": 81
                      },
                      "insertedContent": {
                        "text": "// A simple HTML escaping utility function (can be imported from a library like 'lodash.escape' or 'xss')\nfunction escapeHtml(unsafe) {\n  return unsafe\n    .replace(/&/g, \"&amp;\")\n    .replace(/</g, \"&lt;\")\n    .replace(/>/g, \"&gt;\")\n    .replace(/\"/g, \"&quot;\")\n    .replace(/'/g, \"&#039;\");\n}\n\n// ...\n\napp.get('/search', (req, res) => {\n  const query = req.query.q;\n  const sanitizedQuery = escapeHtml(query || ''); // Ensure query is a string and escape it\n  res.send('<h1>' + sanitizedQuery + '</h1>');\n})"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "properties": {
            "confidence": "HIGH",
            "confidenceScore": 60,
            "confidenceLevel": "HIGH",
            "detectedBy": [
              "Bearer"
            ],
            "autoFixable": true,
            "issueId": "CG-033"
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_express_helmet_missing",
          "level": "warning",
          "message": {
            "text": "[MEDIUM] The application does not use Helmet.js middleware, which is an essential package for Express applications that sets various security-enhancing HTTP headers. Without Helmet, the application lacks protections against common client-side attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) via missing Content Security Policy, clickjacking via missing X-Frame-Options, MIME-type sniffing via missing X-Content-Type-Options, and more.\n\nExploit: Without `X-Frame-Options`, an attacker could embed the application within an iframe on a malicious site and attempt clickjacking attacks, tricking users into clicking on hidden elements. Without a `Content-Security-Policy`, even if HTML escaping is applied, other forms of XSS (e.g., through insecure third-party scripts) become easier.\n\nFix: Add the `helmet` middleware (`app.use(helmet())`) to the Express application after initializing `app` but before defining routes. Helmet automatically sets several HTTP response headers that enhance the application's security posture against various web vulnerabilities, including XSS, clickjacking, and other common client-side attacks, by enforcing browser security policies."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 24
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "Add the `helmet` middleware (`app.use(helmet())`) to the Express application after initializing `app` but before defining routes. Helmet automatically sets several HTTP response headers that enhance the application's security posture against various web vulnerabilities, including XSS, clickjacking, and other common client-side attacks, by enforcing browser security policies."
              },
              "artifactChanges": [
                {
                  "artifactLocation": {
                    "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                    "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                  },
                  "replacements": [
                    {
                      "deletedRegion": {
                        "startLine": 24
                      },
                      "insertedContent": {
                        "text": "const helmet = require('helmet') // Add this line\n\nconst app = express()\napp.use(helmet()) // Add this line before other middleware to apply security headers\napp.use(express.json())\napp.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }))"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "properties": {
            "confidence": "HIGH",
            "confidenceScore": 60,
            "confidenceLevel": "HIGH",
            "detectedBy": [
              "Bearer"
            ],
            "autoFixable": true,
            "issueId": "CG-034"
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_express_reduce_fingerprint",
          "level": "note",
          "message": {
            "text": "[LOW] The Express application, by default, sends the `X-Powered-By: Express` header in its HTTP responses. This header reveals information about the server's technology stack, which can assist attackers in fingerprinting the application and targeting known vulnerabilities specific to Express or Node.js versions. While not a direct vulnerability, it provides useful reconnaissance information to potential attackers.\n\nExploit: An attacker can use network inspection tools (e.g., `curl -I <your-app-url>`) to observe the `X-Powered-By: Express` header in the HTTP response. Knowing the server technology allows them to search for publicly known exploits or vulnerabilities specific to that technology and version, narrowing down their attack vectors.\n\nFix: Disable the `X-Powered-By` header by adding `app.disable('x-powered-by')` after initializing the Express app. This removes unnecessary server technology information from HTTP responses, making it slightly harder for attackers to fingerprint the application and identify potential targets for known exploits."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 24
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "Disable the `X-Powered-By` header by adding `app.disable('x-powered-by')` after initializing the Express app. This removes unnecessary server technology information from HTTP responses, making it slightly harder for attackers to fingerprint the application and identify potential targets for known exploits."
              },
              "artifactChanges": [
                {
                  "artifactLocation": {
                    "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                    "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                  },
                  "replacements": [
                    {
                      "deletedRegion": {
                        "startLine": 24
                      },
                      "insertedContent": {
                        "text": "const app = express()\napp.disable('x-powered-by') // Add this line immediately after app initialization\napp.use(express.json())\napp.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }))"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "properties": {
            "confidence": "HIGH",
            "confidenceScore": 60,
            "confidenceLevel": "HIGH",
            "detectedBy": [
              "Bearer"
            ],
            "autoFixable": true,
            "issueId": "CG-035"
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_lang_observable_timing",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application compares a user-supplied token (`req.body.token`) with a sensitive API token (`process.env.API_TOKEN`) using the standard JavaScript strict equality operator (`===`). This operator is not guaranteed to perform comparisons in constant time across all JavaScript engines and environments. An attacker could potentially perform a timing attack by sending various token prefixes and observing slight differences in response times. These timing discrepancies can reveal how many characters of the provided token match the sensitive stored token, allowing the attacker to progressively guess the full API token character by character.\n\nExploit: An attacker sends a series of requests to the `/verify` endpoint with different initial characters for the `token` parameter (e.g., `token: 'a...'`, `token: 'b...'`, `token: 'c...'`). By precisely measuring the response time for each request, they might observe that a request starting with 'x' takes slightly longer than others. This indicates that 'x' is the first character of the `API_TOKEN`. The attacker then repeats this process with `token: 'xa...'`, `token: 'xb...'`, and so on, gradually reconstructing the entire secret token. Once the token is reconstructed, the attacker gains unauthorized access to resources protected by this API token.\n\nFix: The `crypto.timingSafeEqual` function from Node.js's built-in `crypto` module is used to perform a constant-time comparison of the tokens. This means the function takes the same amount of time to execute regardless of how many characters match or where the first mismatch occurs, thereby eliminating the timing side-channel vulnerability. The `crypto` module should be imported once at the top of the file (e.g., `const crypto = require('crypto');`). Additionally, a check is added to ensure both tokens are valid strings and of the same length before conversion to Buffers, as length differences could themselves be a timing leak. If any of these conditions are not met, `isValid` defaults to `false` to prevent errors and maintain security."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 204
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "The `crypto.timingSafeEqual` function from Node.js's built-in `crypto` module is used to perform a constant-time comparison of the tokens. This means the function takes the same amount of time to execute regardless of how many characters match or where the first mismatch occurs, thereby eliminating the timing side-channel vulnerability. The `crypto` module should be imported once at the top of the file (e.g., `const crypto = require('crypto');`). Additionally, a check is added to ensure both tokens are valid strings and of the same length before conversion to Buffers, as length differences could themselves be a timing leak. If any of these conditions are not met, `isValid` defaults to `false` to prevent errors and maintain security."
              },
              "artifactChanges": [
                {
                  "artifactLocation": {
                    "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                    "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                  },
                  "replacements": [
                    {
                      "deletedRegion": {
                        "startLine": 204
                      },
                      "insertedContent": {
                        "text": "  // The 'crypto' module must be required at the top of the file (e.g., const crypto = require('crypto');).\n  // Perform a constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks.\n  // It's crucial to ensure both inputs are strings of equal length\n  // before converting to Buffers for timingSafeEqual, as length differences\n  // could also be a timing side-channel.\n  const isValid = (token && storedToken && typeof token === 'string' && typeof storedToken === 'string' && token.length === storedToken.length)\n                  ? crypto.timingSafeEqual(Buffer.from(token), Buffer.from(storedToken))\n                  : false;\n\n  if (isValid) {\n    res.json({ valid: true });\n  } else {\n    res.json({ valid: false });\n  }"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "properties": {
            "confidence": "HIGH",
            "confidenceScore": 60,
            "confidenceLevel": "HIGH",
            "detectedBy": [
              "Bearer"
            ],
            "autoFixable": true,
            "issueId": "CG-036"
          }
        }
      ]
